[3] Cholera - Angola (European Response)
Date: Mon, 29 May 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: EUROPA (press release) Belgium [edited]
<http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/06/686&format=HTML&aged=0&language=EN&guiLanguage=en>

The European Commission has allocated a further
1.5 million in Angolan currency in emergency
humanitarian aid to fight the increasing
incidence of cholera in Angola. More than 36 000
cases have been reported since the first outbreak
on 13 Feb 2006. Of Angola's 18 provinces, 11 are
now affected, including the capital Luanda. More
than 1300 people have died and, according to
UNICEF, 35 percent of the victims are children
under 5. This new aid comes on top of an initial
emergency grant of the same amount announced by
the Commission on 21 Apr 2006. At that stage, the
Commission already envisaged the possibility of
mobilizing extra resources, should the need arise.
Epidemiologists now expect as many as 30 000 new
cases over the coming 2 to 3 months. Due to the
rapid spread of the disease, relief agencies and
international bodies like WHO have continued to
scale up their operations. The Commission's
contribution is a vital part of this
international effort.
--
Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D.
<ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
[Clearly the epidemic is not close to being over.
The 10 provinces referred to in this report are
Bie, Bengo, Benguela, Huambo, Huila, Kwanza
Norte, Kwanza Sul, Malanje, Uige and Zaire. Lunda
Norte and Cabinda have now also been affected. -
Mod.LL]
