[9] Diarrhea, Cholera - Bangladesh (Dhaka)
Date: Tue, 23 May 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
<http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/05/23/d60523011410.htm>

Outbreaks of diarrhea, cholera and other diseases
due to the scorching heat of midsummer are
causing a huge rush of patients to different
hospitals in the capital. International Centre
for Diarrhoeal Disease and Research, Bangladesh
(ICDDR,B), Dhaka Medical College Hospital (DMCH),
Mitford and Dhaka Shishu Hospital have been
facing the influx of patients suffering from
these diseases.
Dr Mohammad Shahadat Hossain of ICDDRB told The
Daily Star that though an average of 180-220
patients usually get admitted to the hospital
daily for different waterborne diseases all the
year round, the number increases sharply during
the period of March-May and August-September. On
average, around 450 patients are now hospitalized
daily for diarrheal diseases, he added. Most of
them are children and day-labourers, who work in
the sun.
[Byline: Shaheen Mollah]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Bangladesh can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/banglade.pdf> - Mod.LL]
